And that estimate was appears to have been more of a guess as they really didn't evaluate the vehicle in detail.  My review of the vehicle compared to previous similar accidents with other vehicles which had similar damage but were repaired.  My instincts tell me that they were short of employees and simply didn't have the labor capacity to provide an appropriate estimate or to repair the vehicle.  So, they reported to my insurance that the vehicle was a total loss.  My insurance company then screwed me on the total loss evaluation by using "comparable" vehicles for sale, which had 25-50k more miles than mine, and then they reduced the sales price of those vehicles by 6-8% for "typical buyer negotiations".  Seriously?  "Typical buyer negotiations" in the current used car market?  Used car dealers are getting a big laugh out that statement when I share it with them.  Both insurance companies and body repair shops are teaming up to screw customers.</review>

<Resp>None</Resp>< Review>
Here's a fair warning for people who use this car wash. If the machine "fails" for whatever reason (for me it didn't wash my car at all, I was left with a soapy, wet dirty mess) you are allowed no refunds and they make you wait at the back of the line to go through again.

After waiting 10 minutes in line I was supposed to wait another 15 minutes to go through again.

The supposed manager sat in his chair the entire time, told me my options and made zero effort address the problem and the female staff inside the office were laughing about the situation.</Review>

<Response>None< /Response>< pics>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMDkUDOf1lWVDoCtq0wfpcakAn3_-tuWXb2J6bW=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pics>
< Name>
Kevin Mcnamee< /Name>
< text>
I hosted an 11 mile out and back hike on May 30, 2021 to all three peaks, Mount Pinos, Sawmill Mountain, and Grouse Mountain . The parking is directly at the trailhead and is free.

The trail is a great up and down climb of 5 miles with some switchbacks and plenty of great views all the way up and down. I would say it's more of a moderate to hard hike, I think if you have a few recent 10 mile or so hikes under your belt, you will do just fine. My favorite part is the view from Sawmill Mountain summit. I would also discourage you to do a late start, by the time we got to Grouse Mountain to rest and eat, the flies started coming out on the trail. Also, follow my path, you'll see I had to back track a bit on our way to Grouse Mountain, because AllTrails does not have the trail exactly correct.

Enjoy your hiking.< /text>

This easy < 3 mile round trip hike takes you along a dirt road through majestic stands of Jeffrey pines which in warm weather perfume the air with their mild butterscotch aroma. <GmapID>0x80d95229d05c563f:0x53e22210cb33c312</GmapID>< Text>
In early February, my 93 year old Mama became very ill and had to be taken, via ambulance, to the hospital where she was diagnosed with Influenza A and Sepsis. She stayed in an acute care hospital for one week and was transferred to Paradise Valley Manor and Health Care Center in National City, CA, to get her strength back before she was able to go home and be independent once again.
Upon arrival, we marveled at how neat, clean, and beautifully appointed the facility was inside. The two ladies at the front desk, Sandra and Karina, couldn‚Äôt have been more welcoming and friendly. The various staff members greeted my precious Mama with smiles and compassion and were all so very kind. The Administrator, Aaron Burrup, came in and introduced himself. He shook her hand and made her feel right at home. Amanda, from Admissions, made sure she was comfortable in her room. Her Charge Nurses, Megan, Judy, Edwin, Marisol, and Mila were very helpful and accommodating and worked with us as we shared our concerns. Faye, Karina, and Utzhi, her attentive medication nurses, made certain they continued her regular medicinal regime and if she had a special need, immediately got Doctors orders to help her with whatever arose.
Her CNA‚Äôs were outstanding. Cita, Vilma, Esmer, Cynthia, and Edwina treated my sweet Mom with the same love and compassion they would treat their own Mothers. They would greet her with cheerful smiles and warm hellos many times every day. They sang to her, helped her with her daily personal needs, tenderly helped her shower, neatened her room, and made her laugh. How important these things are when you are yearning to be home to be with your family. They truly become a lifeline.
The housekeepers were amazing at keeping everything neat and clean. I never smelled urine or any other unpleasant odors the entire time my Mom was a patient in this facility.
Her Physical Therapist, Rayne, was extraordinary. Whereas upon arrival, my Mom was so weak and dreaded therapy, Rayne encouraged her and cheered her on as she worked hard and built up her strength. He gave her the support and fortification she needed and taught her skills she will use the rest of her life. Her Occupational Therapist, Lauren, was so patient and thoughtful as she shared her expertise with my Mom so she could eventually go home and live independently again. These two Therapists infused their strength into my Mom and are the reason she is so much stronger now.
With the collaboration of this hard-working, dedicated team, my darling Mama was able to go home today in better shape than before her illness. They provided excellent care for her, both physically and emotionally. Our family is extremely grateful and appreciative to the entire Staff of Paradise Valley Manor and Health Care Center.</Text>

<rate>5</rate><Text>TO PARADISE VALLEY HEALTH CARE CENTER -

With grateful appreciation I would like to thank each and everyone at Paradise Valley Health with all of my heart for the tremendous efforts and real super human compassion in the midst of a very threatening and confusing time for all of us.

<user_name>John Garcia</user_name>< time>
1583271627375<//time>
< text>
I ordered the pan fried noodles with chicken and vegetables, and honestly it was kind of a bland, soggy mess.
The pan fried noodle came to me as an enormous patty, cut into quarters that were each as big as my hand. With no knife at the table or provided with the meal, I basically set those aside and ignored them. It's probably just as well since they were dripping oil.
The broth and meat were amazingly bland. I could not detect flavors of herbs, meats, spices, or even salt while eating. Considering how amazingly fresh the place smells when you walk in, it's kind of a shock that they could make such lifeless dishes.
The wait staff was friendly enough.

Not going back.</text>

<userid>110113259268872205700< /userid><name>Elizabeth Nakahara</name><time>1561249015395</time>< Rate>
4<//Rate>
< Text>
I've eaten here several times and brought friends. The food is very good. I like the broken rice dishes and the vermicelli salads. I especially like the fresh-made drinks, such as the carrot-orange juice. This last visit made me wonder about the Asian middle-aged male waiter, whom I don't think I've seen before. He hung around the table next to me, where 3 men ate lunch. He asked them whether they worked at a nearby tire store, whether business was good, whether they were working especially hard now, etc. It seemed a little forward. When my bill arrived, I remember thinking about how I'd pay the $22.94 owed. I thought I won't leave $25 because the change would not be enough to cover a tip. I decided to leave $40, two $20 bills. I definitely looked at the two bills (I keep $20 bills together, $10 together and $5 together). The waiter scooped up the money the instant I put it on the little plastic tray. He gave me $2 and 6 cents change. He left, so I frantically talked to a waitress who was eating her lunch. I explained I was given change for $25, not $40. She very nicely gave me $17 to make up for the missing change. Then the middle-aged guy returned and said assertively, "You left a $20 bill and a $5 bill; I double checked.'" I was sure I hadn't made such a mistake, but he insisted I did, so I felt resigned to losing $17. When the guy left out the back for a reason unknown to me, the waitress who had reimbursed me $17 said all was fine and I could leave. If that middle-aged waiter takes your money, be sure you get the right change.< /Text>

<Response>None</Response><text>The people are really friendly and I wanted to like the food, but that was not to be.  I only ordered the pho, but if that is any indication, this restaurant needs to fix its cooking or it will die.  I hope the manager or owner is reading this and will take action.  The pho broth could not in any way be called a beef broth.  It looked more like chicken, though weak even for that.  The flavor was utterly bland, and lacking the traditional pho flavors of burnt onion, burnt ginger, anise, clove, and good fish sauce, not to mention any hint of beef.

It's not that hard to prepare.  Boil beef bones, preferably marrow bones, for a couple of days or in a pressure cooker for half a day, add the ingredients described above except for the fish sauce, cook an hour or two more, get rid of the fat, strain, and you have the broth, ready for fish sauce to be added to get just the right salt balance and the final secret weapon of flavor.  Wild fennel is sprouting up around here all over the place now, and the fresh new greens add wonderful flavor for savvy cooks who want to reap the seasonal rewards nature offers up gratis.

Serve with plenty of fresh basil, cilantro, sliced onion and green onion, and sliced green fresh hot peppers for the heat lovers (traditionally, bean sprouts are served with pho too, but I think they detract from the flavor and so I feed them to my dogs, who are very appreciative).  So easy, really.  Most places around here make nice pho broths (check out, among many others, Phuong Nam, Mekong, and Le Cheval, all in Oakland) but Le Pho needs to learn.</text><Gmap_id>0x80857eed3ed9ffa3:0xda6f77b561378dcb</Gmap_id><Time>1493694076268</Time>< user>

<UserId.>112632427227216740791</UserId.><Date>1618178094482</Date><Response>None<//Response><rate>5<//rate><pics>None</pics><name>Nicole Mattson</name><gmapID>0x8094681fdf08c649:0xc524985a70250488</gmapID>< text>

</record></dataset><record>
< Text>
Service was friendly and amazing, their strawberry lemonade was the perfect thirst quencher for this heat. I got the BBQ Pulled Pork Sandwich, and while it was all right, the texture of the thick pickle slices and the flavor overpowered the flavor of the charred pulled pork and other ingredients. Minus the pickles, it was a great sandwich. Their corn bread has got to be hands down the best corn bread I've ever eaten at a restaurant ever, and their honey butter or whatever it is they use is sweet, yet flavorful, and compliments the corn bread perfectly. The bacon and cheese fries came out looking good, and tasted even better than they looked! You can pour the cheese on top yourself, or dip as you please. I am unsure what kind of cheese it is exactly, but it is the perfect cheese to pair with the bacon, without overpowering itself. The fries were evenly seasoned and made with a small crisp, so even though they had their toppings on, they did not get soggy for a while. My friend also had the Santa Ana steak and shrimp or whatever it's called, and the meat was amazing, but they used a type of seasoning that was way too powerful in the pepper area. So he scraped most of the seasoning off, and the meat was a 5/5 again. The atmosphere was busy, but lovely, with a welcoming vibe to it. When it gets busy, they hand you a buzzer, which makes everything easier, so you can step out until it is your turn. The prices were very affordable for the value of the food, and I definitely enjoy that it doesn't cost an arm and a leg for some delicious BBQ. I love coming to this place, and I can't wait to come back.</Text>

< Text>
A comfy atmosphere paired with a friendly and atentive staff make for a wonderful restaurant experience. Having an ATM in the front of the restaurant is definitely a plus, especially if you need to get change for a tip. They have an expansive menu, at affordable prices. They put their lemonades (which are delicious) in mason jars, adding to the country aesthetic they go for. The burgers and other meats my party ordered were perfectly cooked, and delicious. Would recommend to anyone who enjoys steak, or a family friendly restaurant with a friendly atmosphere and good food.< /Text>

<user_name>Simon Hernandez< /user_name>< text>
We came into town Thursday night 10/24.  Checked into our hotel at 830 and already were recommended to Westwoods.  We sat right away and were helped by Beth! (Like the KISS song...bet she's never heard that one before)  Super knowledgeable and patient with first timers.   Portobello Fries, Aged Ribeye, and smoked brisket. 10 out of 10!  Thank you Beth!

We left town today 10/26, Ate at Westwoods again!  This time, we expected a wait, took us longer to be pried from the dessert display, filled with fresh epic carrot cake.
Ally was out waitress and like Beth, knowledgeable,  patient and shes got jokes!  She was selling the move to Fresno very appealing, that and to be closer than 4 hours away. BBQ Bacon burger that has burnt ends with perfectly rendered fat (Easily best burger I've ever had), brisket quesadilla, and pulled pork Nachos...this place can do no wrong.

Id take the long way around to Bishop if it meant visiting Westwoods more often.

And the peppercorn bbq sauce is the perfect mix of steak sauce meets bbq sauce

Thank you Beth and Ally again!!<//text>

<review>I had eaten at this place a few years before and had a great experience. In fact, I had often thought back about the delicious meal and found my mouth watering as I reminisced about the juicy, cooked to perfection tritip Westwood is known for. Upon moving back to Fresno, my excitement grew as my daughter and I headed back for our expected first of many trips to  the beloved restaurant. We settled into our booth, she with her gin and tonic, l with my martini, hungrily awaiting that first bite of meat. I cut into mine and was sorely disappointed. Where was the pink? I had ordered mine medium rare! My daughter's was beautiful; mine was well done! I called over our adorable waiter, Cody, who explained to me that all the trips were cooked the same-medim. Well then, where the heck did my daughter's beautiful medium rare slices come from? To be generous, Cody offered me a new piece of meat, which was brought to the table by a different gentleman who promised a free piece of dessert as a consolation. I cut into the new piece and unfortunately found it to be of the same doneness as the first, only this one also had a large vein of fat running all the way down the middle. I was no longer in the mood for meat, but my carrots were superb! The free dessert, carrot cake tasted like it had been sitting for too long exposed, rather dry, but the gesture was nice. Frankly, however, I think my meal should have been comped! Cody, our waiter, by the way, was a gem! His service could not have been any better!< /review><Pictures>None< /Pictures><Resp>None</Resp>< Gmap_id>

<text>Stopped in for an early dinner/late lunch. I just got the tail end of their lunch pricing and the beginning of happy hour. sweet. I was a party of 1 so I sat at the bar. The interior has an industrial banyardy vibe with lots of metal and wood. I ordered the VIP vodka which has been sitting in pineapple. Its strong but you'd never know it. You can get it at Pismo's too.

I ordered the sampling platter, comes with 2 ribs, fried chicken, tri tip, and 4 small sides. Baked beans are lighter than most. Even with bacon, they have lots of tomato and onion and much less molasses like some other recipes I've seen. He tri-tip was by far the best meat. Soft and succulent, meaty and smoky. The BBQ sauces (regular and pepper) were thick and viscous without being too sweet.<//text>< Pics>

This place has awesome tritip sandwiches! I got the tritip dip and it was amazing! They also have their own signature BBQ sauces and they are great, the peppercorn BBQ sauce is hands down my favorite and you can also by jars of it so you can have the great flavor of westwoods right in your own kitchen. The staff was friendly, the service was fast, and the beer selection magnificent! 10/10 Would eat here again!<//review>

Westwoods has a great western steakhouse atmosphere and the staff were friendly and professional. Unfortunately the food fell short. <Rate>5<//Rate><Review>Stopped here on our way back to Bakersfield from Yosemite.  The place was jammed on a Wednesday night,  25 min wait for a table for two.  No big deal stood at the bar and had a beer with my lady.  We were seated in a booth near the kitchen which I liked because I could see all the food going in and out.  They have a huge staff and they are on top of their game from what I saw.  After talking to our waiter about the questions I had and receiving his recommendations, I went with the Santa Maria tri tip( Medium rare) with the jumbo shrimp. Sweet potato mash and steamed broccoli for sides.  The tri tip was cooked exactly to my likely and it‚Äôs seasoning was excellent.  Sides were also great.  The shrimp were good not great but my attention was on the tri tip and It was quite possibly the best I‚Äôve ever had.  Also a solid glass of Pinot noir for 8 dollars to pair with the tri tip.  The only compliant I could render was that our waiter forgot our salad we ordered to split between the two of us to start and we already had our entrees when I told him.  Once I let him know he quickly brought it out and let me know we were not being charged for it.  That‚Äôs how you do business!  Overall great experience I would return in a heartbeart.

Ps.  My lady loved the look of the place and the exposed wooden beams.</Review>< pics>

<Rating>3</Rating><user_id>102405320006617588972< /user_id><Name>Randy McAtee<//Name><GmapID>0x8094681fdf08c649:0xc524985a70250488< /GmapID><Review>Went there tonight with close friends to celebrate a birthday.  Made reservations in advance for a party of 7.  We were seated immediately upon arrival (but then again, it was 5:30 on a Monday night).

We arrived a little early and I asked the waiter if they had Happy Hour margaritas.  He said he would have to ask.  Why he said that, I don't know because their recording when i called for reservations clearly gave the time for happy hour which ends at 6:00 p.m. (it was probably ~5:25).

Got that cleared up and had my happy hour margarita.  Was good.  Ordered the chips with tri-tip, also good.

Party arrived and we all ordered.  I think most everyone was happy with their meals but you have to keep in mind that 3 in my party of 7 were young men in the their twenties who were easy to please with free beer & food.  They had ZERO complaints.

My friend and his wife said they were happy with their meals, and since they were guest I will try to just take it at face value.

My wife ordered baby back ribs with salad and I ordered their 14 oz rib eye steak with salad.  They had a blurb on the menu about how their beef is aged for 28 days, etc... and so you're expecting something kinda special for the $27 bucks you're paying.

I've eaten steaks from SaveMart that were much better than the one I was served.  It was simply a tough steak.  I didnt even eat it all -- and that's not how I generally roll with a steak   On the positive side I ordered it medium rare and they did a pretty good job on the cooking (maybe a bit more towards medium than the  rare).

My wife's ribs were dry.

When we arrived home my wife commented that she would not choose to return there in the future.  So... it will not be a future destination of choice for us.
___
I give it 3 stars because everyone else (besides the wife and I) seemed satisfied enough.  If it were just my wife and I --> it would give it 2 stars because the salads were good.</Review>< Time>

< review>
First time visitor,
Food was delicious, too many T.V.'s, very loud and one show that I did not need.

To my disbelief there was a child who walked across one of the shared tables four times. At one point the child was lying across the table playing with the parent‚Äôs phone and kicking his feet like this was just a normal day lying around at home. This is not something one is prepared to see in any restaurant. Our server Dean was less than enthusiastic about dealing with the event. After some intense prodding and mentioning that this was an unsanitary practice I convinced him to get the manager. Only after I complained loudly and repeatedly did the patrons who shared the table with this atrocious family and are only six inches from the child walking and lying on their table, actually complain to Dean the server who looked to have the same level of enthusiasm about dealing with the event. When the busser came to clean the table I informed him about the event and suggested that the tablecloth should be changed. After the horrified look left his face he promptly removed the tablecloth. At least one employee recognized that this is unacceptable behavior.

The worst part is that the child's father was laughing and making a joke about the entire event.

I traveled a long way to try this restaurant for my birthday and I doubt I would make the trip again.

I do have one other regret; I did not get a photo or video of this horrific event.

Sincerely,
Mortified in Hanford CA</review>

117416574066040276543</userid>
<user_name>Paula Shapazian</user_name>< Date>
1406409051583<//Date>
<rating>5</rating>< Review>
Okay all of you who were raised in Fresno.....I have great news
for you.....Westwoods has created their version of the
Lesterburger!!!  I could hardly contain myself when I saw that
they had  just added this to their menu!!  I was there for lunch,
and I am hopeful that it will be included on their dinner menu as
well.  Apparently the owner, Mr. Fansler, worked at Lesterburger
growing up and has made a very close version of the original.
Oh how I have missed that burger and I can't thank Mr. Fansler
enough!
The only thing different was that they don't use finely shredded
lettuce as they did in the original, but that's the only difference.
(Remember Al Radka did their TV commercials and used to pull
the shredded lettuce out of the burger and say, "Let us eat it.")
I also must say that the bun they use at Westwoods is
delicious and better than the one used originally.
It's only been 3 days since I had this burger, and it's all I have
been talking about and thinking about.....I want to go back for
another one NOW!!!!
Please, Mr. Fansler, keep this on your menu!!!!!
BTW, service was outstanding!<//Review>
